
Introducing MITRE ATT&CK®
for Cyber Threat Intelligence Training

1. Core Definition: Cyber Threat Intelligence (CTI)
The training adopts Sergio Caltagirone’s definition: CTI is actionable knowledge about adversaries and their activities that enables defenders to make better security decisions and reduce harm.

2. How ATT&CK Enhances CTI
The primary value of using the ATT&CK framework in threat intelligence is the ability to structure data. This allows analysts to:

Compare Behaviors: Contrast different threat groups, track how a single group evolves over time, and compare adversary tactics against existing internal defenses.

Provide a Common Language: It bridges the communication gap between different teams:

Analyst to Defender: An analyst can identify a specific technique (e.g., T1547.001 - Registry Run Keys), and a defender immediately knows which data sources (Registry data) are needed for detection.

Community Sharing: Organizations can share intelligence using standardized IDs that everyone understands.

3. Training Goals
The module outlines five key objectives for the full course:

Understand Utility: Why ATT&CK is the standard for CTI.

Mapping: How to extract ATT&CK techniques from both narrative reports (text-based) and raw data.

Data Management: How to store and visualize mapped data.

Analysis: How to perform actual threat analysis using the mapped data.

Actionability: How to turn intelligence into concrete defensive recommendations.

4. Roadmap of the Training Series
Module 0 sets the stage for the subsequent lessons:

Module 1: Mapping from Narrative Reporting (External reports).

Module 2: Mapping from Raw Data.

Module 3: Storing and Analyzing (Using tools like ATT&CK Navigator).

Module 4: Making Defensive Recommendations.
